Given that the holding company has been engineered solely to make it impossible for  LVMH to acquire a majority stake  of the heritage brand, this seems to me to imply the following: 1) the AMF accepts Hermes' position that LVMH does not have the best interests of the brand at heart, but just wants to make money (horrors!
); 2) Hermes has somehow transcended product status to become synonymous with France, or a certain French heritage/craftsmanship, and the regulators think this deserves protection like any monument.
Of course, this is all speculation - the AMF told Reuters they would publish an explanation of the decision, but it has not appeared yet.

Presumably, the AMF would not extend this protection to just any old luxury handbag makers, which means they have got into the business of aesthetic valuation – and that does not seem like a place they should be.
And who are they to decide LVMH will ruin Hermes?
The luxury conglomerate actually has a pretty good track record with heritage leather goods brands (Vuitton is the cash cow of the company).
Either way, however, I think the opportunity for an outsider to ruin Hermes or re-invent it or keep it ticking along nicely in exactly the same groove should exist.

A row between the leisure entrepreneur Duncan Bannatyne and the TripAdvisor travel website over a negative review of one of his hotels escalated on Monday after the site accused him and his representatives of repeated attempts to intimidate reviewers.

Mr Bannatyne has threatened legal action against the US-based website, which publishes the travel opinions of more than 40m users, after it posted a review from a guest at his Charlton House resort in Somerset that compared it to  Fawlty Towers .
"One of my hotels has recently been a victim of a rogue review, containing obvious lies which I made TripAdvisor aware of," said Mr Bannatyne.
"After I criticised TripAdvisor for failing to act on dishonest and damaging reviews, they removed four five-star reviews in what I can only assume was an attempt to punish me for speaking out."
"However, in the case of Mr Bannatyne's hotels we have had several worrying examples of individuals being intimidated by Mr Bannatyne and his hotel representatives," said Emma O'Boyle of TripAdvisor.

Ms O'Boyle added: "TripAdvisor has a zero tolerance approach on bullying as we defend the freedom of speech, hence why we duly sent a letter to the Bannatyne's Charlton House Spa Hotel manager stating that we do not condone this behaviour."
A spokesman for Mr Bannatyne refuted the claims of bullying, saying it was TripAdvisor that was bullying small UK hotel owners.
He said Mr Bannatyne had only retweeted a Twitter post that detailed the phone number of a negative reviewer, adding that TripAdvisor had refused to speak to him directly.
Steve Kaufer, TripAdvisor's chief executive, said he was unaware of Mr Bannatyne's complaint but added that the website's users should be allowed to express a full range of opinion.

The row comes at a time when the government looks set to abandon its backing for official tourism ratings schemes, on the grounds that they are less relevant and up to date than websites such as TripAdvisor.
